20","1141":"1141","1184":"1184","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"Abt 1141–":"omkring 1141–Afdød","1141–Male":"1141–Afdød","1179–Male":"1179–Afdød","1184–1242":"1184–1242","1120–1205":"1120–1205","1121–1205":"1121–1205","Abt 1141":"omkring 1141","1205":"1205","1179":"1179","1121":"1121","1242":"1242","1120":"1120","1141":"1141","1184":"1184","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1141–":"circa 1141–Overleden","1141–Male":"1141–Overleden","1179–Male":"1179–Overleden","1184–1242":"1184–1242","1120–1205":"1120–1205","1121–1205":"1121–1205","Abt 1141":"circa 1141","1205":"1205","1179":"1179","1121":"1121","1242":"1242","1120":"1120","1141":"1141","1184":"1184","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1141–":"about 1141–Deceased","1141–Male":"1141–Deceased","1179–Male":"1179–Deceased","1184–1242":"1184–1242","1120–1205":"1120–1205","1121–1205":"1121–1205","Abt 1141":"about 1141","1205":"1205","1179":"1179","1121":"1121","1242":"1242","1120":"1120","1141":"1141","1184":"1184","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chevaler","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Pierre, Patrice, Serge, Gabrielle, Jacques, Marcel, Michel, Raoul, Sylvain, Adelore, Antoine.","French: from Old French <i>chevalier</i> ‘knight’ (literally ‘horseman, rider’, from Late Latin <i>caballarius</i>, a derivative of <i>caballus</i> ‘horse’). In the Middle Ages only men of comparative wealth were able to afford the upkeep of a riding horse. It is likely that in the majority of cases the surname was originally a nickname, or an occupational name for a knight's servant, rather than a status name, for most men of the knightly class belonged to noble families which had more specific surnames derived from their estates. This was a name of Norman origin in England but probably did not survive the medieval period, and was later reintroduced by Huguenot refugees.","History: Joseph Chevalier from Dieppe in Seine-Maritime, France, married Françoise-Marthe Barton in Montreal, QC, in 1670. Pierre Chevalier <i>dit</i> Labbé and Duchesne from Pont-l'Abbé-d'Arnoult in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie-Madeleine Ménard in Montreal, QC, in 1697. — In North America, this surname was originally also a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Alexis Dulignon <i>dit</i> Chevalier (a descendant of Jean Dulignon from La Rochefoucaud in Charente, France), who married Judith (de) Billy in Louiseville, QC, in 1778. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Cavalier","meanings":["French (southern): variant of   Chevalier   ‘knight, rider’. This surname is also found in Britain, where it is of Huguenot origin.","History: André Cavalier from Bordeaux in Gironde, France, married first Isabelle-Barbe Brousillon in New Orleans, LA, <i>c.</i> 1760, and second Marie-Jeanne Le Cossec/Cosse in New Orleans in 1770."]},{"name":"Chevallier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Blanchard, Christophe, Francois.","French: variant of   Chevalier   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Franc","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of   Franco ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Franc Chevaler was born about 1141, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Franc, was 23 and his mother, Wymark, was 22. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1141–":"umbes 1141–Surnud","1141–Male":"1141–Surnud","1179–Male":"1179–Surnud","1184–1242":"1184–1242","1120–1205":"1120–1205","1121–1205":"1121–1205","Abt 1141":"umbes 1141","1205":"1205","1179":"1179","1121":"1121","1242":"1242","1120":"1120","1141":"1141","1184":"1184","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1141–":"noin 1141–Kuollut","1141–Male":"1141–Kuollut","1179–Male":"1179–Kuollut","1184–1242":"1184–1242","1120–1205":"1120–1205","1121–1205":"1121–1205","Abt 1141":"noin 1141","1205":"1205","1179":"1179","1121":"1121","1242":"1242","1120":"1120","1141":"1141","1184":"1184","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1141–":"environ 1141–Décédé","1141–Male":"1141–Décédé","1179–Male":"1179–Décédé","1184–1242":"1184–1242","1120–1205":"1120–1205","1121–1205":"1121–1205","Abt 1141":"environ 1141","1205":"1205","1179":"1179","1121":"1121","1242":"1242","1120":"1120","1141":"1141","1184":"1184","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque William Franc Chevaler est né environ 1141, à Gloucestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, John Franc, avait 23 ans et sa mère, Wymark, avait 22 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils et 1 fille."},"de":{"Abt 1141–":"um 1141–Verstorben","1141–Male